[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(8) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Thou hast shewed great mercy unto David.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou, thou hast done great kindness with David.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (The regular phrase; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:72",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) From this point the relation here is briefer on the whole than that of Kings. The greater part of the long verse (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 3:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is omitted, and the variations between the two texts become numerous, though the general sense is the same in each.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And hast made me to reign in his stead.—Comp. 1Kings 3:7; and the similar language of Esarhaddon, king of Assyria (B.C. 681-668): “Ever since Asshur, Samas, Bel, Nebo . . . made me, Esarhaddon, sit securely on the throne of my father” (Cuneiform Inscriptions of Western Asia, 3:15, Colossians 2).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And hast made me to reign in his stead.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 3:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; and the similar language of Esarhaddon, king of Assyria (B.C. 681-668): “Ever since Asshur, Samas, Bel, Nebo . . . made me, Esarhaddon, sit securely on the throne of my father” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Cuneiform Inscriptions of Western Asia,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " 3:15, Colossians 2).",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:8",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 1:8",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And hast made me to reign — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Give me the spirit of my father David, that Israel may not suffer by the change. The eminence of those that went before us, and the obligation that lies upon us to keep and carry on the good work they were engaged in, should quicken our prayers for wisdom and grace, that we may do the work of God in our day as faithfully as they did in theirs.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1:1-17 Solomon's choice of wisdom, His strength and wealth. - SOLOMON began his reign with a pious, public visit to God's altar. Those that pursue present things most eagerly, are likely to be disappointed; while those that refer themselves to the providence of God, if they have not the most, have the most comfort. Those that make this world their end, come short of the other, and are disappointed in this also; but those that make the other world their end, shall not only obtain that, and full satisfaction in it, but shall have as much of this world as is good for them, in their way. Let us then be contented, without those great things which men generally covet, but which commonly prove fatal snares to the soul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The verbal differences between this passage and the corresponding one of Kings ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:5-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are very considerable, and indicate the general truth that the object of the sacred historians is to give a true account of the real bearing of what was said: not ordinarily to furnish us with all or the exact words that were uttered. The most important point omitted in Chronicles, and supplied by Kings, is the conditional promise of long life made to Solomon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; while the chief point absent from Kings, and recorded by our author, is the solemn appeal made by Solomon to the promise of God to David his father ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which he now called upon God to \"establish,\" or to perform.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
