  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou hast showed great mercy unto David my father",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". These also are the exact words found in the parallel place, but they omit the words, \"thy servant,\" before \"David,\" found there. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And hast made me to reign in his stead",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This concise expression takes the place of two equivalent expressions, found at the end of the sixth and beginning of the seventh verses in the parallel passage, the former of which passages also describes it as \"this great kindness,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " kindness on the part of God - a description very much in harmony with David's own grateful acknowledgment to God (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Up to this point our present account differs from its parallel in cutting out Solomon's eulogy of his father (\"According as he walked before thee in truth and in righteousness and in uprightness of heart with thee\"), and his humbler disparagement of himself (\"And I, a little child, know not how to go out or come in\"). 2 Chronicles 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The theophany, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:5-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In that night, i.e., on the night succeeding the day of the sacrifice. The appearance of God by night points to a dream, and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:5-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we are expressly informed that He appeared in a vision. Solomon's address to God, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:8-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:6-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " given more at length. The mode of expression brings to mind ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 17:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and recurs in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 6:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". מדּע, with Pathach in the second syllable, elsewhere מדּע (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
